The volume of a cone is given by

\begin{align*}
V = \frac{1}{3}\pi r^{2} h
\end{align*} By the physical application of the
problem, we can assume that the base radius of the cone changes as the
height increases. First, we should express the radius of the cone as a
function of its height.

By similar triangles, and the fact that \emph{r} = 1 when \emph{h} = 10,
we find that the following relation holds:

\begin{align*}
\frac{r}{h} = \frac{1}{10}\quad \iff \quad r = \frac{h}{10}
\end{align*}

Thus the volume of the shell can be expressed entirely in terms of
\emph{h}:

\begin{align*}
V &= \frac{1}{3} \pi \left(\frac{h}{10}\right)^2 h \\
&= \frac{\pi}{300}h^{3}
\end{align*}

The rate of change in the volume of the cone can be computed by
differentiating V with respect to t, giving us

\begin{align*}
\frac{dV}{dt} = \frac{\pi}{100}h^{2} \cdot \frac{dh}{dt}
\end{align*}

Since we are told that the height of the cone changes at a constant rate
of 0.1 cm/year, the rate of change of in the cone's volume when \emph{h}
= 10 cm and \emph{r} = 1 cm is given by

\begin{align*}
\frac{dV}{dt} &= \frac{\pi}{100} (10 \text{cm})^2 \cdot 0.1 \frac{\text{cm}}{\text{year}} \\
&= {\color{blue} \frac{\pi}{10} \, \frac{\text{cm}^{3}}{\text{year}} }
\end{align*}

